  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use my US doctors with Aetna International?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Aetna International members have full access to Aetna's domestic US network of 1.7 million+ providers. Your existing Aetna network doctors will accept your international plan with direct billing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Aetna handle pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Aetna uses full medical underwriting. Pre-existing conditions are typically excluded from coverage, sometimes permanently, sometimes for a defined period (2+ years). There's no moratorium option where conditions become covered after claim-free years.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between Pioneer and Navigator plans?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Pioneer plans are tiered (basic/mid/premium) with set benefit packages. Navigator plans are modular—you start with core hospital coverage and add modules (outpatient, dental, maternity, etc.) as needed. Navigator offers more customization but can become complex.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is maternity covered?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Maternity is available but has a 12-month waiting period on Pioneer and Pioneer Prime. Pioneer Platinum includes maternity from day one. The waiting period means you must be enrolled for 12 months before pregnancy-related claims are covered.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I exclude US coverage to save money?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Excluding US coverage reduces premiums by approximately 30-40%. However, without US coverage, Aetna's main advantage disappears. At that point, Allianz Care or IMG Global may offer better value for pure international coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the CVS Health connection benefit me?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">CVS Health's $350B+ backing provides financial stability. In the US, you may benefit from CVS MinuteClinic access and CVS pharmacy integration. The main benefit is knowing your insurer won't go bankrupt.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna International is the clear choice for US expats who need seamless stateside coverage.</strong> The integrated Aetna network, direct billing at US hospitals, and competitive pricing (when US coverage is included) make it the best value for Americans abroad.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, if you don't need US coverage, Aetna loses much of its competitive advantage. European expats or those with no US ties will likely find better value with Allianz Care, IMG Global, or AXA. And if mental health coverage is a priority, BUPA Global's parity model may be worth the premium.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bottom line:</strong> For US expats, Aetna International is excellent. For everyone else, shop around.
  </p>

